R Community Explorer - R User Groups

Ben Ubah, Claudia Vitolo and Rick Pack

August 16, 2019

Background

Few days ago we announced an open-source dynamic dashboard that is built using R and Javascript for R-Ladies. We have since extended that work to encompass R user groups in general that are organized on Meetup.

Why a dashboard to track R user groups globally now?

  1. It is probably worthwhile to realize the bias representation of the popularity and usefulness of the R language by several authors and rating systems over time and it seems reasonable to start presenting some facts in an open-source data-driven manner. It would definitely be advantageous to developers and other related decision makers to see the popularity of languages based on the growth of their user groups and group memberships over the years. This dashboard tries to provide a way to track the growth of R user groups, membership and their geographical distribution.
  Chart showing Cumulative Growth of R User Groups
  1. For a community to flourish, finding information easily from a unified resource is possibly an advantage. Information regarding R user groups is spread across several sources and each source displays only a portion of this information. A list of some sources we found are:

  • Jumping Rivers: https://jumpingrivers.github.io/meetingsR/r-user-groups.html

  • RConsortium: https://www.meetup.com/pro/r-user-groups/

  • R-Ladies: https://gqueiroz.shinyapps.io/rshinylady/

  • Meetup.com: https://www.meetup.com/topics/r-project-for-statistical-computing/

We therefore engaged in building a more comprehensive information resource that has aggregated much of the data in the last three sources listed above since they are all organized on the Meetup platform. Our next target are those groups that are not organized on Meetup that are compiled by Jumping Rivers. Please reach to us if you know of other resources we could explore.

  1. For decision making, R centered organizations may need to geographically measure the presence of R users and groups for events planning, diversity programs, and other activities that could expand the use of the R langugage in under-represented regions.

  2. New and existing R users would have a resource through which they can find groups near them and see how to get involved.

  3. R has some reputation for a thriving community and we want it to get even better.

The R Consortium

Two out of three top-level R Consortium projects are focused on R user groups and it is our thought that their involvement with support R user groups has contributed to the growth of the R community. The map on this dashboard is optimized to point Inactive and Unbegun R user groups to R Consortium’s RUGS grant program to help sustain these groups.

Classifying R User Groups

It was quite challenging to classify R user groups on Meetup at the beginning of this coding phase. The reason was:

  1. The names of some R user groups on Meetup comprise of “Location” + “R User Group” (e.g. “Las Vegas R User Group”) in their Meetup names, but in their topics or areas of focus, they do not mention R.

  2. The names of some R user groups on Meetup comprise of “Location” + “Data Science/Analytics Group” in their meetup names (e.g. Charleston Data Science), but in their topics or areas of focus, they mention “R Project for Statistical Computing”

  3. There are other groups that have Python, Julia, KNIME, Hadoop, etc in their Meetup names, but yet mention “R Project for Statistical Computing” in their areas of focus. Some groups combine R and other tools in their names and topics.

  4. Apart from “R Project for Statistical Computing”, many groups (R-focused and data-science in general) identify with the R language by selecting one of the following topics or areas of focus such as “Programming in R”, “Data Science using R”, “R Programming Language”, and several others.

  5. Another group of names are those like useRs, PhillyR, BelgradeR, etc

It was quite easier to find R-Ladies groups on Meetup because they maintain a consistent naming structure across all groups - “R-Ladies” + “Location” (e.g. R-Ladies Madison). Only one find_groups() call from the meetupr package was sufficient. But this was just not the case for R user groups in general.

Our Solution

Curtis Kephart generously provided us a key to solving this problem - a technique based on string matching that he uses to retrieve upcoming R events. We extended his approach and this is what we did:

  • Retrieve all data science groups on Meetup (7700 +) and use string matching to select groups that contain strings like “r user”, “r-user”,“r-lab”,“phillyr”,“rug”,“bioconductor”,“r-data”,“rug” in their Meetup URL names. We then re-select a second time using string matching to search for strings like “programming-in-r”,“r-programming-”,“-using-r”, “r-language”, “r-project-for-statistical” in the groups’ topics field.

  • Retrieve all user groups that mention “r-project-for-statistical-computing” in their topics separately

  • Retrieve all R-Ladies groups separately. We tried to use string matching to retrieve R-Ladies groups from the data science groups above, but some groups were left out.

  • Combine all the resulting data frames and remove duplicates.

Every other approach we tried left out some R user groups. If you have any further ideas, we are glad to hear from you.

What Has Been Achieved

For the R user groups dashboard, the following were achieved:

  1. We used the meetupr package to extract R user groups from Meetup.com
  2. Improved the existing find_groups() and get_events() functions in meetupr to meet our requirements and switched from Meetup API keys to OAuth 2.0 authentication system.
  3. Transformed the data from Meetup to required formats
  4. Persisted the data on GitHub
  5. Developed a static HTML dashboard interface based on open-source Bootstrap template.
  6. Rendered the persisted data via the dashboard interface.
  7. Automated the process
  8. Deployed it via GitHub Pages

Some Highlights from the Dashboard

  1. A leaflet map with markers and pop-ups filled with information about the user groups’ membership, events, status, and inactive and unbegun groups could obtain R Consortium grants.
  1. A cluster map to aggregate markers in clusters and provide cluster counts using leaflet-markercluster.js Javascript library.
  1. Top destinations for R user groups based on membership across 6 regions.

The Tools We Used

To accomplish the following, we used a mix of the tools listed below:

  1. R, RStudio and the following packages:
    • meetupr, curl, jsonlite and leafletR
  2. Javascript and the following libraries: jquery.js, d3.js, echarts.js, leaflet.js, leaflet-markercluster.js and lodash.js
  3. Gentelella Admin Dashboard Bootstrap HTML template
  4. Travis CI to build the project, execute R scripts and bash commands
  5. Bash commands to call R scripts and commit modified files to GitHub

How We Achieved It

  1. We used the meetupr package to retrieve R User Groups from meetup.com with an R script.
  2. We further analyzed this data and computed several summaries out of it. We used the leafletR package to transform our data frame to GeoJSON. We used this GeoJSON file to create a leaflet map using leaflet.js. In this map, R user groups are separated into three groups with markers of three color categories: Active (blue), Inactive (dark-blue), and Unbegun (orange). Active groups have had an event in the past 180 days or have an upcoming event in the future. Inactive groups have not had an event in the past 180 days and do not have an upcoming event. Unbegun groups have not had an event in the past and none are planned for the future.
  3. Persisted all data and our summaries in CSV / JSON files. After each Travis build, the data and our summaries gets updated straight from the Meetup API.
  4. We wrote bash commands to run our R scripts, and commit updated CSV / JSON files to GitHub after every Travis build.
  5. We setup Travis Cron Jobs, to build this project daily and update our data.
  6. We then, customized the Gentelella Admin Dashboard Bootstrap HTML template to our requirements.
  7. Rendered our summaries via widgets on this dashboard. Used Javascript/libraries to perform other simpler summaries and produce maps, charts and tables.

The Result

The final product is a dashboard for R User Groups that is updated daily via Travis, built using R and JavaScript and hosted via GitHub Pages.

At the time of writing, there are 617 R User Groups composed of 494,000 + members, across 74 countries, 374 cities, with more than 13,000 past events and 200 upcoming events. 63% of R user groups are active, 26% are inactive, and 11% are unbegun. Unbegun groups have members but have not started organizing events yet. Our observation is that members are added to the R community daily.
